rewritten_review:
Best Stephen King film alongside IT, though this one is more fun than scary. 

This one's got it all: 

-a great cast with a Alice Krige and Brian Krause and a fun cameo from King himself; 

-well dosed horror in an amusing storyline; 

-great use of music, Santo & Johnny's "Sleepwalk" in particular; 

-likeable characters in a typical King setting: middle of nowhere village; 

-lots of humor. You can't really get good scares here because it's too much fun and over the top; 

-old but really nice makeup effects like they don't make anymore! 

A 4,5 rating: I don't get it really. I mean, seriously, when you think about it, this film truly showcases a unique blend of elements that are rare to find all together in one movie. The casting choices are impeccable, with Alice Krige and Brian Krause delivering standout performances that make their characters both intriguing and relatable. And, of course, Stephen King's cameo adds that extra layer of delight for King enthusiasts who always look forward to seeing him make an appearance in adaptations of his work. The balance of horror and amusement in the storyline is perfectly executed, ensuring that viewers are engaged without feeling overwhelmed by fear. 

The music, particularly Santo & Johnny's "Sleepwalk," is used to great effect, creating an atmosphere that is both nostalgic and hauntingly beautiful. It's a soundtrack choice that complements the film's tone wonderfully. The setting, a typical King-style middle of nowhere village, adds to the charm, providing a backdrop that feels both familiar and unsettling. The characters are not only likeable but are also developed in a way that makes their interactions enjoyable to watch. 

Humor plays a significant role in this film, offering a refreshing take on the horror genre. The scares are present, but they're delivered with such a sense of fun and exaggeration that it's hard not to be entertained. The makeup effects, while old school, are crafted with such care and detail that they stand out as a testament to the artistry that went into making the film. It's a kind of craftsmanship that seems to have become a rarity in modern horror films, which often rely heavily on CGI. 

When was the last time a horror film was as much fun as this one? It's a question worth pondering, as this film manages to capture a sense of entertainment and enjoyment that leaves a lasting impression.
